\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1: Hermitian (33 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In homework, you showed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times{}$
\end_inset

 was Hermitian under the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\vec{F},\vec{G}\rangle=\int\overline{\vec{F}}\cdot\vec{G}$
\end_inset

; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\overline{\nabla\times\vec{F}}\cdot\vec{G}=\int\overline{\vec{F}}\cdot\nabla\times\vec{G}$
\end_inset

, for appropriate boundary conditions, and from that you went on to show
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\nabla\times{}$
\end_inset

 was Hermitian and positive-semidefinite, and hence Maxwell's equations
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}\vec{E}}{\partial t^{2}}=\nabla\times\nabla\times\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 had oscillating solutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The case you analyzed in homework only applied to Maxwell's equations in
 vacuum, however.
 In materials, the equations become 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial^{2}\vec{E}}{\partial t^{2}}=\varepsilon^{-1}\nabla\times\left(\mu^{-1}\nabla\times\vec{E}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 are material properties related to the magnetic and electric polarizability
 of matter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 are real, positive scalar functions, 
\series bold
choose an inner product and show
\series default
 that the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=\varepsilon^{-1}\nabla\times\mu^{-1}\nabla\times{}$
\end_inset

 is Hermitian and positive semidefinite, and hence that we still have oscillatin
g solutions.
 Don't worry about the boundary conditionsâ€”just assume that we have chosen
 boundary conditions so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times{}$
\end_inset

 is still Hermitian as above (i.e.
 so that boundary terms vanish when you integrate by parts, i.e.
 you can just use the integral identity from above).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2: Timestepping (34 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a PDE 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}=\hat{A}u$
\end_inset

, that we discretize via finite-differences as in class into a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Crank-Nicolson
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 scheme:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\vec{u}^{n+1}-\vec{u}^{n}}{\Delta t}=A\frac{\vec{u}^{n+1}+\vec{u}^{n}}{2},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{n}$
\end_inset

 denotes the (discretized) 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=n\Delta t$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a discretized version of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 finite differences in space if 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 consists of spatial derivatives like 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
From class, the left-hand side is a second-order accurate (errors 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim\Delta t^{2}$
\end_inset

) center-difference approximation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=(n+\frac{1}{2})\Delta t$
\end_inset

.
 That requires the right-hand side to also be at time 
\begin_inset Formula $n+\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If we treat 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{n}$
\end_inset

 as an approximation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}(n\Delta t)$
\end_inset

, show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\vec{u}^{n+1}+\vec{u}^{n}}{2}\approx\vec{u}([n+\frac{1}{2}]\Delta t)+O(\Delta t^{2})$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 it is second-order accurate.
 (This was claimed in class but not proved.
 Use the Taylor series.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose our matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

) satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $A=A^{*}\prec0$
\end_inset

 (negative definite).
 Show that the solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{n}$
\end_inset

 of our finite-difference scheme above go to zero as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 (Hint: write 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{n}=(\text{something})^{n}\vec{u}^{0}$
\end_inset

 as in class and write the eigenvalues of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

something
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in terms of the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.) i.e.
 show it is unconditionally stable (for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t>0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3: Born (33 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}(p)=-\nabla^{2}+c(p,\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 in some domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 with Dirichlet boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.u\right|_{\partial\Omega}=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c(p,\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 is a real-valued function that depends on some parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a real number).
 Suppose that I tell you that I have a computer program that can quickly
 and accurately solve 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{A}(0)u=f
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 given any right-hand side 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

.
 That is, I can apply 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}(0)^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Explain how, using my 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}(0)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 computer program (without modifying it), you can compute
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.\frac{\partial u}{\partial p}\right|_{p=0}.
\]

\end_inset

Hint: write the solution for a 
\emph on
small
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p$
\end_inset

 approximately using a Born approximation, then take the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p\to0$
\end_inset

 limit.
 Assume you can Taylor-expand 
\begin_inset Formula $c(p,\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 around 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

